[[File:Aboriginal man, Bilin Bilin, sitting outside a tent at the Deebing Creek Aboriginal Mission, ca. 1900.jpg|thumb|Bilin Bilin, at the [[Deebing Creek Mission|Deebing Creek Aboriginal Mission]], circa 1900]]
'''Bilin Bilin''' (born c. 1820; died 1901) was a member of the [[Yugambeh people|Yugambeh]] [[Bundjalung people]] in Australia, who gained respect of the [[History of Queensland#Nineteenth century|European colonials]] and received a [[king plate]] for it. Alternate names for him include Jackey Jackey, Kawae Kawae, John Logan, and Bilinba.

Bilin Bilin chose to work with the Europeans and be friendly to [[Christianity]], in so much as distributing [[Bible|Bibles]], while maintaining his [[Australian Aboriginal culture|traditional beliefs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/first_australians/resistance/bilin_bilin|title=Bilin Bilin - National Museum of Australia|website=www.nma.gov.au|accessdate=15 May 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508225107/http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/first_australians/resistance/bilin_bilin|archivedate=8 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In his case, favoring diplomacy over confrontation helped his ability to stay on his ancestral land for most of his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2008/02/13/2161380.htm|title=Calling Descendants of Bilin Bilin|date=13 February 2008|website=www.abc.net.au|accessdate=15 May 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311023221/http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2008/02/13/2161380.htm|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  His [[diplomacy]] included demanding equal wages for his people and encouraging them not to leave their land. A [[Lutheranism|Lutheran ]]Pastor, Haussmann, taught him to read and write.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://missionaries.griffith.edu.au/resource/frontier-relations-logan-district|title=Frontier Relations in the Logan District - German Missionaries in Australia|website=missionaries.griffith.edu.au|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>

