{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Otto Lauffer | honorific_suffix = | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1874|02|20|df=y}} | birth_place = Weende, now part of [[Göttingen]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1949|08|08|1874|02|20|df=y}} | death_place = [[Hamburg]] | death_cause = | resting_place = [[Ohlsdorf Cemetery]], location R9 (29-30) | resting_place_coordinates = approx. {{Coord|53|37|18|N|10|2|16|E|region:DE-HH_type:landmark|display=inline}} | monuments = | residence = | nationality = [[German people|German]] | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Göttingen]] | occupation = {{Plainlist| * [[Folklore|Folklorist]] * [[Cultural History|Cultural historian]] }} | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | television = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = | website = }}
'''Otto Lauffer''' (20 February 1874 – 8 August 1949) was a [[German people|German]] [[Folklore|folklorist]] and [[Cultural History|cultural historian]].
== Life == Otto Lauffer was born in Weende<ref>{{cite book | last=|first=| editor-last = Brückner,|editor-first = Wolfgang|editor2-last = Beitl| editor2-first = Klaus|title = Volkskunde als akademische Disziplin: Studien zur Institutionenausbildung. Referate eines wissenschaftlichen Symposions vom 8.-10. Oktober 1982 in Würzburg|trans-title=Folklore as an Academic Discipline | series = Sitzungsberichte, Österreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften Philosophisch-Historische Klasse (Vienna) | volume = 414 | publisher = Österreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften | isbn = 9783700105855 | page = 87| chapter= |trans-chapter=| quote = }}</ref> (which is today is a district of [[Göttingen]]) on 20 February 1874 and spent his childhood there, until 1886.
He studied German language and literature studies, history and art history in [[University of Göttingen|Göttingen]] (enrolled on 22 August 1891), [[Berlin]], [[Munich]] and again in Göttingen (enrolled 24 April 1894). In 1896 he was awarded his doctorate under the supervision of [[Moritz Heyne]].
In 1902, Lauffer became an assistant{{Clarify|date=August 2012}} at, and in 1907 director of the [[Historical museum, Frankfurt|Historical Museum]] in [[Frankfurt]]. From 1908 until the opening in 1922, he oversaw the building of the [[hamburgmuseum|Hamburg History Museum]] (now "hamburgmuseum"), continuing in his role as director until 1946.
In the same year that the [[Universität Hamburg|University of Hamburg]] was founded, Otto Lauffer was granted the first professorship in folklore in Germany, which he retained until 1939. In 1922/23, he was also rector of the University.
Lauffer died on 8 August 1949 in [[Hamburg]], and was buried in the [[Friedhof Ohlsdorf|Ohlsdorf Cemetery]] there (grave reference: ''R9 (29-30)''). His collected works are to be found in the [[Hamburg University Library]]. On 20 February 1984, a memorial plaque was decidated to his memory in Weende.
The {{lang|de|Otto-Lauffer-Straße}} in Weende and the Otto Lauffer barge in Hamburg are named after him.
<!-- Not finished translating == Working life == Due to the fact that the posts of museum director and university professorship were both held by the same person, folklore in Hamburg took a special direction after the Second World War, with the focus initially being placed on researching the culture of property.
